  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Si-free steel (M1-IA) achieved PSE of 61 GPa% vs. 41 GPa% for Si-containing steel (M2-IA).",
    "Stacking fault energy (SFE) of both steels is below 18 mJ/m², favoring TRIP effect during deformation.",
    "Austenite stability is influenced by local Mn enrichment due to insufficient diffusion during 1 h IA, leading to higher-than-expected Mn in some grains (>12%).",
    "Grain size heterogeneity: austenite grains < 0.5 µm exhibit higher stability due to finer size and higher carbon concentration.",
    "In M2, Si partitions from austenite to δ-ferrite and α-ferrite during IA, affecting austenite composition and stability.",
    "Critical IAT exists above which full retention of equilibrium austenite is not expected; for M1 at 700°C, calculated retained austenite was only ~16%, but observed was 45%, explained by additional stabilizing factors.",
    "For M2-IA, calculated retained austenite ~11% vs. observed ~19%, also explained by local heterogeneity but to a lesser extent due to lower fraction of fine grains.",
    "Fractography: HR samples show cleavage fracture (brittle), IA samples show dimple rupture (ductile).",
    "Strain hardening rate curves show three stages; stage II gradual decline corresponds to TRIP effect, with end values 1338 MPa (M1-IA) and 989 MPa (M2-IA).",
    "Post-tensile EBSD phase maps show austenite reduction from 45% to 6.5% (M1) and from 19% to 3.2% (M2), confirming TRIP.",
    "δ-ferrite in M2 introduces additional partitioning of Mn and C into austenite, contributing to stability but also leads to strain partitioning observed in KAM maps."
  ]
